## The one that stops people talking.

There are tombs you admire and tombs you photograph, and then there is Nefertari, which does something else entirely: it silences people. Visitors step down into it chattering and step out a few minutes later without much to say, because there is nothing quite adequate to say. The colour is the reason. Three thousand two hundred years old, and the blues and golds and deep earth-reds look as though the painters left an hour ago — a whole small underground world of goddesses and stars and offerings, intact, luminous, and impossibly fresh.

It is, by broad agreement, the most beautiful room in Egypt. And you get about ten minutes in it.

## Why ten minutes, and why that's the point

The tomb is not busy because the authorities won't let it be. To protect the paint from the breath and the humidity of crowds, entry is capped to a small number of visitors a day, on a timed ticket, for roughly ten minutes each. It is expensive, and it sells out, and people who turn up hoping to buy at the gate are routinely turned away.

That scarcity is exactly why it's worth doing properly. We secure your slot in advance, brief you fully before you go down — so you're not spending your precious ten minutes squinting at a guidebook — and time your whole morning around the entry. You walk in, you look, and for those minutes the finest painted room in the ancient world is, quietly, yours.

> Ramesses built it for the queen he loved and wrote it on the wall: "the one for whom the sun shines." Standing in it, you understand the sentiment completely.

## A love letter you can stand inside

Ramesses the Great had many wives and one favourite, and when Nefertari died he poured the full weight of Egypt's artistry into her tomb — not a king's monument to himself, but a husband's monument to a wife. That's the feeling the room gives off, once your Egyptologist has told you the story: not grandeur, but tenderness, on an epic scale.

Come for the colour. Stay, in the ten minutes you're given, with the fact that someone loved someone enough to build this — and that thirty-two centuries later, you're the one who gets to see it.
